Sun Wukong also known as the Monkey King, is a mythological figure who features in a body of legends, which can be traced back to the period of the Song dynasty. He appears as a main character in the 16th century Chinese classical novel Journey to the West. He is a monkey born from a stone who acquires supernatural powers through Taoist practices. After rebelling against heaven and being imprisoned under a mountain by the Buddha, he later accompanies the monk Xuanzang on a journey to retrieve Buddhist sutras from "the West". Sun Wukong possesses immense strength; he is able to lift his 13,500 jÄ«n (7,960 kilograms ) staff with ease. He is also extremely fast, able to travel 108,000 li (21,675 kilometres ) in one somersault. (Note that this is more than half way around the world). Sun knows 72 transformations, which allow him to transform into various animals and objects; however, he is troubled in transforming into other forms, due to the accompanying incomplete transformation of his tail. Sun Wukong is a skilled fighter, capable of holding his own against the best warriors of heaven. Each of his hairs possess magical properties, capable of being transformed into clones of the Monkey King himself, and/or into various weapons, animals, and other objects. He knows spells to command wind, part water, conjure protective circles against demons, and freeze humans, demons, and gods alike. One of the most enduring Chinese literary characters, Sun Wukong has a varied background and colorful cultural history. Sun Wukong's origin is from the White Monkey legends from the Chinese Chu kingdom (700â€“223 BC), who revered gibbons and especially white-colored ones.These legends gave rise to stories and art motifs during the Han dynasty, eventually contributing to the rise of the Sun Wukong figure. Sun Wukong was initially developed as a Taoist immortal before being incorporated into Buddhist myths. He is also considered by some scholars to be influenced by elements of both Chinese folklore and the Hindu deity Hanuman from the Ramayana. . . #throwback #singapore #bencoolen #travelphotography #instagood #instalike #pictoftheday #photooftheday #photography #like4like #nikon

CreatureS | Savour Comfort On A Plate . . We know that everyday and everthing thing we do is setting the table for you, but while it's our food table, it's your story to tell. Let's face it, no one ever left home to find the ordinary in anything - the same goes for food. We all love to discover something exciting, different and special. But we always always always love to return to the familiar, the comforting and the memorable. . . At CreatureS, our food table is a constant reminder, to not forget self discovery, to express our point of view and to present our art. Last time I was watching Channel News Asia when I saw them featured the Tang Shipwreck cargo that are now displayed in a museum in New York. Suddenly I realized that I was able to see the display personally (for free) last time I visited the Asian Civilisations Museum in Singapore. I was also blessed to unearth some of their collections through the virtual reality experience that the museum offered. Now I'm sharing you some of the photos from my visit.  How significant are these art pieces? The remarkable cargo of more than 60,000 mostly perfectly preserved ceramics discovered from the shipwreck in Java Sea on 1998 has revolutionized the way we see the world in the 9th century.  Upon inspection, it was realised that this was a trade vessel transporting works of art to sell in the Middle East. Until then, historians had had no record of trade routes between the Far East and the Middle East existing in the mid-800s AD.  The discovery also showed that the Chinese artists were making their products more desirable to their Middle Eastern buyers, incorporating styles and motifs that were popular thousands of miles away in Persia. Among the pieces were three dishes with blue and white colouring, which changed our understanding of Chinese ceramics.  The museum curator said that the traditional dating for blue and white is around 14th century but in this shipwreck we saw that they were actually producing blue and white in the 9th century.Â The blue is from cobalt and cobalt was only available in the Middle East in that period.  The beautiful objects of exceptional rarity testify to the ingenuity of artists and merchants, and show that exotic objects have long been appreciated by the worldâ€™s consumers. Thereâ€™s a certain kind of surprise that comes from realising that these global connections were in existence more than 1,000 years ago because people today think of globalisation as something that is very recent.  #JustMyDay #MyTravelDiary #TangShipwreck #Arts #History #ACM #Museum #Singapore #Discovery #Archeology #Ceramics #Science #FineArts #Blue #Antique #Cargo #Ship #Navigation #ë§íŒ” #ì‹±ê°€í¬ë¥´ #ëŒ€ë°• #adventure #CNA

[Petua Penjagaan Cik Bunga Agar Kekal Bersih] . Petua 1 : Bagi wanita yang Cik Bunga selalu berair dan berbau kurang menyenangkan, eloklah mencuba petua ini. Ambil segenggam serbuk teh, letakkan ke dalam mangkuk. Tuangkan air panas, kemudian duduklah di atas mangkuk itu sehingga wapnya terkena faraj anda selama 2 minit. Selepas itu basuh rata-rata dengan air teh itu. Lakukan 2 kali pada waktu pagi dan malam. . Petua 2 : Ambil 2 biji kulit pisang muda, 3 helai daun sireh bertemu urat, sebiji kulit pinang, gambir sebanyak 3 keping dan sedikit kapur sireh. Ramuan tersebut hendaklah ditumbuk sehingga lumat. Kemudian direndamkan dengan setengah baldi air suam panas. Basuhlah faraj anda dengan air tersebut 2 kali sehari pagi dan malam agar ia sentiasa bersih dan segar. . Petua 3 : Untuk mengetatkan Cik Bunga, rebus biji manjakani dan air rebusan itu dijadikan bahan pencuci Cik Bunga. Cik Bunga akan kembali ket.at dan tidak mengeluarkan bau busuk yang amat sangat. . Petua 4: Yup! Ni paling cepat dan semua petua di atas ada lengkap dalam satu botol. Yang ni paling mudah. Guna je Celebrity Feminine Scrub Wash. RM 59.00 CFSW semua dah siap touch n go sahaja. â€œA dangerous adventure that almost took my life, turned into one that changed it.  Home to the worldâ€™s third highest peak - the Kanchenjunga - Goechala is perhaps the best trek anyone can go for amidst the huge mountains in India.  Against the warnings of the villagers, I went ahead with the trek despite it being the monsoon season. I started having difficulty breathing as I slipped into having altitude sickness as I made my way up.  I was half conscious by this point and almost fell off a ledge. Luckily my guide grabbed me just in time, and he dragged me to the next checkpoint where I continued hyperventilating while he tried to warm me up. I was already having flashbacks of my family by then.  Eventually through medication, hot liquids, and lots of blankets to warm me up, I was conscious enough to make my way down. What if I actually died? I realised I hadnâ€™t done much in life, and I knew I had to change.  I had 3 more weeks in India, and my cousin who was with me offered the chance to make a difference. Together we took a trip to Rajasthan, where we lived amongst the people there, understood their struggles, and during our stay, we also came across a school a school in disrepair, with no filtered water or even toilets.  That was how our social enterprise The Project Nomad @theprojnomad came to be. Skipping my internship and having that incident in the mountains definitely changed my entire perspective on life, and it is something I wouldnâ€™t trade for anything else.â€ -Nasrul  #millennialsofsingapore  #millennials #singapore #yoursingapore #igsg #sgig #instasg #qotd #youth #singaporean #millennialsofsg

Walking around Singapore we came a cross a kid and his dad spinning flaming steel wool for a photography project (photographers will get it, non photogs may not but you just need to know this is the result ;) ). It's tough to miss; it's basically a ring of fire, this time at night in Singapore along the river. So I chatted him up and took some photos.  None of us were actually from Singapore. One topic we discussed was the legality of spinning fire in circles here. You don't want to break the law in Singapore!  Eventually we moved from out in the open along the river to this spot under a bridge.  Anyway I got some shots that he (the fire spinner) liked and I told him I'd email him when I got back to NY around mid April. I guess he got nervous and posted on Reddit after a few days passed looking for me.  https://www.reddit.com/r/newyork/comments/62ndgi/looking_for_a_new_york_photographer_who_was_near/dfojul4/?context=3 << turns out this post is about me.. Shoutout to my college buddy Alex Black for making the connection (and asking 'What color hair does he have?' ... LEBIH BANYAK MENDENGAR  Diantara fitnah orang yang berilmu (orang alim) ialah berkata-kata lebih disukai daripada mendengar. Padahal mendengar itu lebih selamat daripada berkata-kata karena dalam berkata-kata orang cenderung untuk mengisi, menambah dan mengurangi. (Yazid bin Abi Habib)  Penjelasan : Setiap manusia tentu saja ingin mengubah sesuatu dalam hidupnya menjadi lebih baik. Berbicara memang tak pernah salah, tetapi terkadang kata-kata atau kalimat yang muncul dari mulut kita justru menjadi bumerang bagi diri sendiri. Mendengarkan orang lain mungkin akan lebih baik, kita bisa mengambil sisi positif dari kalimat yang diucapkan orang lain.  Yang mesti kita ingat adalah tidak ada manusia yang dapat menjadi ahli dalam berbagai hal, meskipun menurut orang lain kita cerdas, meskipun menurut orang lain kita bijaksana, maka akan menjadi lebih cerdas dan bijaksana jika kita mampu mengelola kemampuan kita menjadi lebih optimal dengan tanpa banyak mengeluarkan banyak kalimat.Â  Rahasia kehebatan orang-orang besar bukan terletak pada banyaknya dia berbicara di depan umum, tetapi pada banyaknya tindakan dalam membuktikan hal-hal yang ia dengarkan dari orang-orang kecil yang justru bukan siapa-siapa, yang tak punya pangkat dan kedudukan. Saya pernah berbincang dengan rekan, juga dokter keluarga, artinya kalau diantara keluarga kami sedang mengalami gangguan kesehatan, kami akan berkonsultasi dengannya. Suatu ketika dia bilang; makan itu jangan hanya enak dimulut saja, tapi, buat perut akan menjadi masalah. Artinya, makanan yang enak itu, gurih, lezat, misal yang pakai bumbu penyedap MSG, atau santan kelapa misal pada soto dan ketupat sayur. Yang pertama ini saya paling suka, soto kaki, daging atau campur dengan iso atau usus sapi, atau jarit, paru atau daging yang masih bercampur lemak. Lantas, beberapa hari lalu saya berkunjung ke bywalk, Muara karang. Sebuah mall dengan pemandangan laut. Sungguh menggoda saat saya pesan sop buntut dengan buntut sapi yang di grill alias dipanggang. Fresh, dengan aroma bumbu kecap, bawang putih, lada. Belum sop bening yang dipisah dengan irisan wortel, kentang, daun seledri, aroma biji pala dan kayumanis. Berapa lama digodoknya untuk sop? Enam jam pak, sahut pelayan resto itu. Oh. Saya teringat sop buntut resto yang ada di Hotel Borobudur, Jakarta. Makin lama di masak dengan api kecil makin lezat buntut api dengan mengeluarkan kaldu. Oh iya kolesterol masih aman, dengan meminum obat. Tapi,tetap terkendali memasukkan makanan kedalam perut. Starting on a new novel! ğŸ˜ƒ The author, Dawn Farnham, lived in Singapore for many years and was a docent with the Asian Civilisations Museum. It was there that she apparently got inspired to write these stories.  What was envisioned as a trilogy has since become a series of four volumes called The Straits Quartet. The Red Thread is the first book in the series!  My distributor & dear friend Leslie knows I'm into historical fiction at the moment and he's been a great recommender of books. 1830s Singapore? ğŸ˜  Aargh, that man!  So when I finished Balli Kaur Jaswal's book, Leslie's recommendation piqued my interest enough for me to do the unethical thing: I let this book jump my queue.  I have no idea whether I'll like it ~ I have not read any of her books. But as long as I know Farnham was herself intrigued by Singapore's colourful past and did thorough research (it's a journalist thing), I'm game for her to unleash her creativity and imagination on this historical platform.  Coolies. Peranakan family. 18-year-old Scots girl. Love. Fate. Saat Sperma Bertemu Sel Telur  Awal percobaan pembuahan terjadi ketika Anda dan pasangan sedang menikmati hubungan seksual. Saat mencapai orgasme, penis pria mengeluarkan cairan mani yang kaya dengan sperma ke dalam vagina. Cairan ini melesat ke dalam rahim mencari jalan untuk bertemu dengan sel telur. Kontraksi lembut pada rahim membantu sperma hidup dalam saluran reproduksi mencapai sel telur. Sperma-sperma akan melakukan perjalanan sepanjang kurang lebih 18 cm dari leher rahim ke tuba falopi di mana sel telur biasanya berada. Sperma pertama yang bertemu dengan sel telur akan berusaha menembus cangkang sel agar terjadi pembuahan. Umumnya sperma-sperma ini dapat berenang dengan kecepatan 2,5 cm tiap 15 menit. Beberapa sperma dapat menghabiskan waktu setengah hari untuk mencapai tujuan. Sementara sperma tercepat biasanya mencapai sel telur dalam waktu 45 menit. Pembuahan harus terjadi dalam waktu 24 jam setelah sel telur dihasilkan. Setelah salah satu sperma berhasil menembus sel telur, sel tersebut berubah bentuk sehingga sperma lain tidak bisa menembus masuk. Saat itulah janin terbentuk. Namun jika sperma tidak juga menemukan sel telur untuk dibuahi, mereka dapat tetap bertahan dalam tuba falopi hingga 7 hari setelah hubungan seksual. Jika dalam 7 hari tersebut wanita mengalamiÂ ovulasi, maka pasangan tersebut akan mendapatkan keturunan.  #miom #kista #azoospermia #asi #kistsurvivor #miomsurvivor #bayi #holistik #bengkulu #medan #rahim #singapore #melaka #malaysia #thailand #pejuangasi #pejuangkanker #bumil #kiathamil #anakbunda #anakkeren #freekonsultasi #ektopik #bayipintar #herbalBEE #herbalholistik #pcos #bumilssehat #bajubayi

â€œI got into theatre by complete accident. When I was in secondary one, I wanted to join the choir, but my school had this policy where students had to audition for every performing arts group thatâ€™s made available to them. Somehow, I ended up in Chinese Drama  Back then, my Chinese was terrible. During the audition, they made me read this really difficult passage with a lot of words I didnâ€™t even know. They also asked questions like why I was there and why I wanted to join the club.  For every Chinese word I spoke, I spoke about 10 English words; it was the worst audition ever. When I got in, I had to use a classroom ruler to match my name to the assigned club, just to make sure they had me in the right place  Iâ€™m effectively bilingual now partly because of my training in Chinese drama, but I think my Chinese was horrible because I read a lot of English books growing up. My parents also spoke primarily in English, so I had a hard time communicating with my grandma as a kid.  Apparently, I rolled around the floor and pretended to be a ball because I didnâ€™t know how to convey that I wanted an orange. It took her half an hour to figure out what I wanted. I even told my mom one time that I wasnâ€™t Chinese, and she was absolutely horrified!  My first memory of learning Chinese? I was five. I was actually bullied in kindergarten because I wasnâ€™t like the other kids. Everyone was very Chinese-speaking and it gave me social anxiety. The trauma made me associate Chinese with â€˜bad peopleâ€™ and English with my safe environment.  Now that Iâ€™m older, I think itâ€™s very important to have a grasp of both English and your Mother Tongue. Beyond the cultural significance, itâ€™s what helps you communicate with people. My Cantonese, for instance, is very subpar, but I can at least understand what my grandparents are saying.  Iâ€™m even learning French and Malay. My father is Malaysian, and learning the language helps bridge my Malaysian relatives and I. Sometimes they would crack jokes and I would go â€˜Uh huh! I get it!â€™. Itâ€™s really cool when you donâ€™t need someone to translate something for you, and you feel like you can get to know somebody better.â€ - Esther, 23

Dry and hard rice that tastes like it's been in the fridge for too long, slightly tough beef, and dried truffle slices devoid of any fragrance or flavour except for a barely there nuttiness. I really needed the honey truffle soy to moisten things up a little, but there was barely any of it, and what I was left with was the bad synthetic aftertaste of really cheap tasting truffle oil. - Service was slightly bumbling, and the food was on par with previous experiences at other branches, which is to say, not good. The only redeeming factor is pints of Archipelago go for $9++ during happy hour. - Platypus Kitchen Santa Grand Hotel East Coast

With its unique mix of ten bungalow homes and thirty semi-detached units, Michaelâ€™s Residences is a premium development set in the heart of the lush natural greenery that extends from the nearby Dairy Farm Nature Park. Wholly designed and developed by ONG&ONG, this splendidly luxuriant residence is the result of a successful collaboration achieving a collective goal, which was to offer the sophisticating consumer public a fresh residential concept. . Minimal bounding and demarcation allows the individual gardens fluidity, converging to form a lush communal green space, connecting the entire development. Balancing the boldness of the communal garden are subtle features that delineate spaces within the Michaelâ€™s grounds. From boundary cues in the form of postboxes and concealed security gates, to understated shifts in material that distinguish different areas within the development. . The Michaelsâ€™ development also considers aspects of sustainable, tropical living â€“ a philosophy that ONG&ONG champions. Cross-ventilation design principles are embodied into the spatial layout, with generous overhangs and moveable screens introduced to shield homes the elements.
